 classically.
 For example, the nature might roll an tetrahedron die with 
\begin_inset Formula $\{LLL,LRR,RLR,RRL\}$
\end_inset

 in its four faces.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $LRR$
\end_inset

 were face-down, the measurement result for three electrons would be 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Furthermore, this tetrahedron die might not be accessed by human for some
 reasons so that we think we are handling a system constituting three electrons.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to verify EPR's idea, we need to analysis the idea of probability
 more carefully.
 Imagining somebody tosses a coin behind a veil, we heard the coin is tossed,
 but cannot see the result.
 Although the probability for us is still 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}(\{H\})=\mathbb{P}(\{T\})=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, we know the coin behind the veil must be either head or tail face-up.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In classical probability, there is no difference between the coins have
 not been tossed or the coins have been tossed but we do not know.
 However, there is a difference when we consider the quantum probability.
 Because the three electrons can be specially separated, and each electron
 can be measured along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 axis separately, if the nature actually rolled the tetrahedron die, this
 die should be rolled before the electrons are separated and measured.
 In another word, there should be a period that the human observer would
 not know the measurement results for each electron along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 axis, but the nature should know.
 The result for 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th electron is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\sigma_{x}^{j}\right)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\sigma_{x}^{1}\right)w\left(\sigma_{x}^{2}\right)w\left(\sigma_{x}^{3}\right)\in\{LLL,LRR,RLR,RRL\}$
\end_inset

, i.e., the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\sigma_{x}^{1}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\sigma_{x}^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\sigma_{x}^{3}\right)$
\end_inset

